==Belief== During the Nanboku-cho period, a famous [[samurai]] named [[:en:Nitta Yoshioki|Nitta Yoshioki]], the second son of [[Nitta Yoshisada]], fought for the Imperial [[Southern Court]] in Japan's North-South divide. Yoshioki was known for his bravery and strategic wisdom, and his death in a cowardly attack at the Yaguchi Ferry marked the end of his legacy.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Tetsudōshō |first1=Japan |title=An Official Guide to Eastern Asia: Trans-continental Connections Between Europe and Asia ... |date=1914 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1v1MAAAAYAAJ&dq=Nitta+Shrine++Nitta+Yoshioki&pg=PA21 |language=en}}</ref> The samurai warriors who were responsible for Yoshioki's death were believed to have been cursed by his vengeful spirit, which caused them to experience terrifying ghostly phenomena that included lightning strikes and fire balls. To appease Yoshioki's spirit, local villagers constructed a shrine at the site of his death, based on the Japanese belief of "Goryo Shinko," which involved enshrining the spirits of deceased individuals who could protect people from harm. This belief was widely held across Japan and helped to mitigate the fear of natural disasters and plagues that were often attributed to evil spirits.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Joly |first1=Henri L. |title=Legend in Japanese Art: A Description of Historical Episodes, Legendary Characters, Folk-lore, Myths, Religious Symbolism, Illustrated in the Arts of Old Japan |date=1908 |publisher=J. Lane |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OSxPAAAAYAAJ&dq=Nitta+Shrine++Nitta+Yoshioki&pg=PA408 |language=en}}</ref>
